{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17598659","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17598659"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:42:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:42:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15498"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15498","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15498"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.32,0,0.26,0.4]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8189"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61628"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8189"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15498"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47081"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6812"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19821"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19825"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61628","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61628"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with progressive shortness of breath over six months. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Cardiac examination reveals a loud P2 and a right ventricular heave. Chest X-ray shows enlarged pulmonary arteries. Echocardiogram reveals elevated pulmonary artery pressures.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a characteristic pathological finding in pulmonary arterial hypertension?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreased muscularisation of small arteries","Endothelial cell proliferation","Decreased fibroblast activity","Alveolar haemorrhage","Bronchial smooth muscle hypertrophy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPulmonary arterial hypertension (PAH) is characterised by progressive remodelling of the pulmonary vasculature. The pathological changes involve multiple cell types and processes that lead to vessel wall thickening and luminal narrowing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndothelial cell proliferation\u003C/strong\u003E is a key pathological feature of PAH. Dysregulated endothelial cell growth leads to intimal thickening and the formation of plexiform lesions, which are complex vascular structures pathognomonic for severe PAH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased muscularisation\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as PAH actually involves increased muscularisation of small pulmonary arteries. This process, known as medial hypertrophy, contributes to vessel wall thickening and increased vascular resistance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased fibroblast activity\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as PAH involves increased fibroblast proliferation and activation. These cells contribute to adventitial thickening and extracellular matrix deposition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlveolar haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E is not a typical feature of PAH. While hemoptysis can occur in severe disease, it is not part of the primary pathological process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchial smooth muscle hypertrophy\u003C/strong\u003E is not a characteristic feature of PAH, which primarily affects the pulmonary vasculature rather than the airways.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pulmonary arterial hypertension (PAH) is characterised by vascular remodelling including endothelial proliferation and muscularisation of small arteries.","Plexiform lesions are pathognomonic for severe PAH and represent complex vascular structures with endothelial cell proliferation.","Increased fibroblast activity and extracellular matrix deposition contribute to vascular remodelling in PAH."],"references":["Tuder RM. Pathology of pulmonary arterial hypertension. Semin Respir Crit Care Med. 2009 Aug;30(4):376-85. doi: 10.1055/s-0029-1233307. Epub 2009 Jul 24. PMID: 19634077.","Schermuly RT, Ghofrani HA, Wilkins MR, Grimminger F. Mechanisms of disease: pulmonary arterial hypertension. Nat Rev Cardiol. 2011 Jun 21;8(8):443-55. doi: 10.1038/nrcardio.2011.87. PMID: 21691314; PMCID: PMC7097518.","Montani D, G\u00fcnther S, Dorfm\u00fcller P, Perros F, Girerd B, Garcia G, Ja\u00efs X, Savale L, Artaud-Macari E, Price LC, Humbert M, Simonneau G, Sitbon O. Pulmonary arterial hypertension. Orphanet J Rare Dis. 2013 Jul 6;8:97. doi: 10.1186/1750-1172-8-97. PMID: 23829793; PMCID: PMC3750932.","Mason, R. J., Broaddus, V. C., Martin, T. R., King, T. E., Schraufnagel, D., Murray, J. F., \u0026 Nadel, J. A. (2010). Murray and Nadel\u0027s textbook of respiratory medicine E-book: 2-volume set. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47081"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15498"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47081"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-15T23:31:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-15T23:32:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8189"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61628"}}},"meta":{"